ggplot

Start off by reading this paper on the motivations and structure behind the ggplot library. It should give you an excellent background for how to think about a ggplot object, as well as introductions into common terms.

A Layered Grammar

I love this paper, and the ggplot2 package, because it presents a very different philosophy of data visualization than many of us think about. Were trained to think about graphics as scatter plots, or bar charts, or coxcomb diagrams, when in reality what were seeing is a set of shapes that correspond to some data, overlaid on top of a common scheme for understanding that data. A plot is, very literally, nothing but shapes stacked on top of each other, and thinking about them in that way allows you an immense amount of freedom in how you design them. ggplot strikes an excellent balance between allowing you the freedom to do whatever you like with your visualizations and providing you with excellent defaults if you dont want to get too far into the weeds.

Now that you know some theory, lets put it into practice! This page is designed to give you some basics of plotting in ggplot2. Whenever you print a plot, it will show up in the Plots tab in the panel to the bottom right of your RStudio session.

A quick note about terminology: Wickham described ggplot as a layered grammar, but to avoid confusion I think modular might be a better term. As youll notice when were constructing a plot below, layer actually has a specific meaning in ggplot: its an instance of a single geom function (that is, something that actually draws data onto the screen in the form of some shape). The other plot components, like labels and faceting and coordinates, are added on in the same way geoms are, but they are not referred to as layers. For clarity, Ill refer to any modularized plot component as a component, and only to layers specifically as layers.

ggplot functions are unlike anything else youll see in R, because they work by adding functions to each other. You literally stack things on top of each other, using the + sign to add a new component. Get used to this grammar!

Plotting Salaries

Loading Libraries and Data

As always, we need to start by loading libraries: in this case we want car to load our data, data.table to wrangle it, and ggplot2 to plot it. What would we do to load those libraries, load the Salaries dataset, and convert that dataset to a data.table? Hopefully, you remember:

library(car)
library(data.table)
library(ggplot2)

data(Salaries)
Salaries <- data.table(Salaries)

Say we want to make a scatterplot, with yrs.since.phd on the x-axis and salary on the y-axis. Lets walk through this, piece by piece.

Bare ggplot

Every ggplot command will begin with the function ggplot(). This will create an object of type ggplot, to which you can then add the rest of your plot components. Lets start by making a completely empty ggplot object:

base_plot <- ggplot()
print(base_plot)


This is nothing. Just a grey background. But youll notice that weve now created an object called base_plot, of type ggplot, that has some properties:

class(base_plot) # what type of object is this?
## [1] "gg"     "ggplot"
base_plot$layers # No layers so far, just an empty list
## list()
base_plot$data # No data associated with it 
## list()
## attr(,"class")
## [1] "waiver"
base_plot$mapping # Nothing is "mapped" onto this dataset yet
## * NULL ->


Data

Our first step should be to associate some data with this plot data is the first argument to ggplot():

base_plot <- ggplot(data=Salaries)
print(base_plot)


Still no change to what we see, but look at base_plots data attribute now:

base_plot$data
##          rank discipline yrs.since.phd yrs.service  sex salary
##   1:     Prof          B            19          18 Male 139750
##   2:     Prof          B            20          16 Male 173200
##   3: AsstProf          B             4           3 Male  79750
##   4:     Prof          B            45          39 Male 115000
##   5:     Prof          B            40          41 Male 141500
##  ---                                                          
## 393:     Prof          A            33          30 Male 103106
## 394:     Prof          A            31          19 Male 150564
## 395:     Prof          A            42          25 Male 101738
## 396:     Prof          A            25          15 Male  95329
## 397: AsstProf          A             8           4 Male  81035


Theres data there now! We just need to tell ggplot what to do with it!

Mappings

We use the sub-function aes() to create mappings within ggplot. (aes stands for aesthetic.) Any time you want to take the values of a column in your dataset and represent them on your plot somehow, thats called a mapping, or an aesthetic. In this case, we said that we want to map yrs.since.phd to the x-axis position, and salary to the y-axis position. So, we include an aes function as an argument in our ggplot function:

base_plot <- ggplot(data=Salaries, aes(x=yrs.since.phd, y=salary))
print(base_plot)


Now were getting somewhere! Weve imposed a range to the axes, which comes with some default labeling and grid lines. Our base_plot$data attribute still looks the same, and now we also have a couple of mappings:

base_plot$mapping
## * x -> yrs.since.phd
## * y -> salary

Layer 1: Points

Weve said that we want a scatterplot, but wheres the scatter? Well, up to this point we havent told ggplot how we want to represent our data, so it hasnt drawn anything. We need to use one of our many geoms to describe how we want to draw the data on the page. For a scatterplot, we use a function called geom_point(). This is a new plot component, so it gets added on top of our ggplot function with a + sign:

layer_1 <- ggplot(data=Salaries, aes(x=yrs.since.phd, y=salary)) +
          geom_point()
print(layer_1)


Hey-o! That looks like a real plot! Lets see what the layers look like on this one:

layer_1$layers
## [[1]]
## geom_point: na.rm = FALSE
## stat_identity: na.rm = FALSE
## position_identity


These are some details for a geom_point layer.

A New Mapping: Color

What if we wanted each of these points to be a different color, based on the rank of each professor? Well, we have a column named rank, and we want to map it to color, so we need to put it in an aes() function:

layer_1 <- ggplot(data=Salaries, aes(x=yrs.since.phd, y=salary, color=rank)) +
          geom_point()
print(layer_1)


I personally prefer to associate colors with specific layers, so I would actually do something like this:

layer_1 <- ggplot(data=Salaries, aes(x=yrs.since.phd, y=salary)) +
          # notice how I associate this mapping with the *layer*, not the plot as a whole
          geom_point(aes(color=rank)) 
print(layer_1)


Layer 2: Best-Fit Lines

Ok, so now Ive made this nice scatterplot, and the general trend seems to be that more years since Ph.D corresponds to a higher salary. Id like to verify this by putting one of those nice best-fit lines1 through my data. There are rigorous ways to do this that well get to shortly, but a nice shortcut is a function called geom_smooth(). By default, geom_smooth will fit a curve called a loess to the data, so if we want to fit a straight line, we need to pass it the method argument "lm", for linear model:

layer_2 <- ggplot(data=Salaries, aes(x=yrs.since.phd, y=salary)) +
          geom_point(aes(color=rank)) +
          geom_smooth(method="lm")
print(layer_2)


If you do layer_2$layers, youll see that weve added a second layer to our ggplot object, for our best-fit line.

I dont love that this line is blue it interferes with the blue of the points behind it. I want to change it to black. Should this be inside an aes() function, or not?

Hopefully, you said no Im not trying to map any column of my dataset to the color of the line, I just want to change the color of the line. I can do that directly inside my geom_smooth function, no aes() needed:

layer_2 <- ggplot(data=Salaries, aes(x=yrs.since.phd, y=salary)) +
          geom_point(aes(color=rank)) +
          # notice the *absence* of an aes() function below
          geom_smooth(method="lm", color="black")
print(layer_2)


Faceting

Remember faceting? Its another term for making subplots by splitting your dataset based on some column in the dataset. So, for example, if I wanted to split my data by sex, and make a subplot for each, I would do:

faceting <- ggplot(data=Salaries, aes(x=yrs.since.phd, y=salary)) +
          geom_point(aes(color=rank)) +
          geom_smooth(method="lm", color="black") +
          # adding a facet_wrap component
          facet_wrap(~sex)
print(faceting)


Notice the format of the argument to facet_wrap does it look familiar? Its a formula object, just like what we used for reshaping last lecture, except that theres nothing on the left side of the ~.

You can also facet in two different directions, using the facet_grid function. This is where the fact that the argument is a formula starts to make sense: the subplots are split into rows" by whatever is to the left of the ~, and into columns by whatever is to the right of it:

faceting <- ggplot(data=Salaries, aes(x=yrs.since.phd, y=salary)) +
          geom_point(aes(color=rank)) +
          geom_smooth(method="lm", color="black") +
          # here's a facet_grid component instead
          facet_grid(discipline~sex)
print(faceting)


You can add the argument scales="free" to ether facet function to remove the imposition of shared scales:

faceting <- ggplot(data=Salaries, aes(x=yrs.since.phd, y=salary)) +
          geom_point(aes(color=rank)) +
          geom_smooth(method="lm", color="black") +
          facet_grid(discipline~sex, scales="free")
print(faceting)

Labels

The default labels that come with this plot arent the most clear theres no title, and my axis labels are just my column names, which arent super readable. I can change all three of those things with the labs() function:

labels <- ggplot(data=Salaries, aes(x=yrs.since.phd, y=salary)) +
          geom_point(aes(color=rank)) +
          geom_smooth(method="lm", color="black") +
          facet_wrap(~sex)+
          # adding labels
          labs(title="Years Since Ph.D and Salary, by Sex, Discipline and Rank",
               x="Years Since Ph.D",
               y="Salary (USD)")
print(labels)


And that there is a clean, attractive, layered, faceted, mapped, and labeled ggplot object! Weve made a nice plot, and explored how each component of it is modular, removable, and customizeable.

In this example Ive just explored one geom type: geom_point. But there are literally dozens of others! Play around with them yourself, try starting with a simple plot and building up to a complex one. the ggplot cheat sheet and the R for Data Science chapter on ggplot will both help you, especially with tricky geoms like geom_bar.

Examples of Common ggplot Geoms

I havent included labels/titles in these to make them as simple as possible. Also see the ggplot cheat sheet for many more details.

Bar Plots & Relatives

## Notice two things about this code. 
## First of all, I use the `fill` argument to `aes` instead of `color`,
## because I want to *fill* in the bar. Using the `color` argument will only color the outline of the bar. 

## Secondly, I don't specify a "y" aesthetic.
## By default, `geom_bar` makes a histogram, which counts how many rows there are in each element 
## and plots that as the "y" value.
ggplot(Salaries, aes(x=rank)) +
  geom_bar(aes(fill=rank))

## Here I want a bar plot with a `y` compoent that I specify: the mean salary, by rank.  
## I do this by adding a `y` aesthetic, but I also have to change the `stat` argument in `geom_bar`
## so it knows to expect that `y` argument.

## Notice also that I *aggregate* my dataset down to mean values in order to make this plot make sense. 
## What would happen if I ran this code on the entire dataset?
ggplot(Salaries[, list(mean.salary=mean(salary)), by=list(rank)], aes(x=rank, y=mean.salary))+
  geom_bar(aes(fill=rank), stat="identity")

Line plots

There isnt a natural use for a line plot in the data as it stands, because were not tracking individuals over time (or any other variable) our data is cross-sectional. To prove it to you, heres what happens if I try to make a line plot with the data as it stands:

ggplot(Salaries, aes(x=yrs.service, y=salary)) +
  geom_line()


Yikes, what a mess! It would be better to take the mean value across our x-value first:

mean_salary_by_service <- Salaries[, list(mean.salary=mean(salary)), by=list(yrs.service)]
ggplot(mean_salary_by_service, aes(x=yrs.service, y=mean.salary))+
  geom_line()


Thats better! It would be nice to include a scatter plot of the original data behind it, so we can see what data were taking the mean of. This involves attaching a different dataset and different aesthetics to each geom:

ggplot() +
  ## The 'alpha' argument denotes *transparency*: 1 is fully dark, 0 is invisible
  geom_point(data=Salaries, aes(y=salary, x=yrs.service), alpha=0.7)+ 
  geom_line(data=mean_salary_by_service, aes(y=mean.salary, x=yrs.service))


Notice how different my plotting code looks here. My ggplot object is completely empty, and I have a different data argument and different aes components for each geom. In general, the ggplot functions should contain whatever arguments and aesthetics you want to apply to the entire dataset, and the geom functions should contain only those things that apply to a single geom specifically.

Density Plot

Density plots are kind of like smooth histograms they show you the distribution of a single value in your dataset.

ggplot(Salaries, aes(x=salary)) +
  # notice the use of both "fill" and "alpha" here:
  geom_density(aes(fill=sex), alpha=0.5)

Reshaping and ggplot

Why did I spend all that time last lecture telling you about reshaping? When is it useful? Well, lets take a look back at that cereal dataset:

# load MASS library and UScereal dataset
library(MASS)
data(UScereal)

# save the names of cereals as an actual row, instead of an index value
UScereal$cereal_name <- rownames(UScereal) 

# convert to a data.table
UScereal <- data.table(UScereal) 

# clean up some column values
UScereal[, shelf:=NULL] # we won't need that column
UScereal[, sodium:= sodium/1000] # this converts the units of the "sodium" column from milligrams to grams

# rearrange the column order
setcolorder(UScereal, c("cereal_name", "mfr", "vitamins", "calories", "protein", "fat", "sodium", "fibre", "carbo", "sugars", "potassium"))
print(head(UScereal))

## 2:                  All-Bran   K enriched 212.1212 12.121212 3.030303
## 3: All-Bran with Extra Fiber   K enriched 100.0000  8.000000 0.000000
## 4:   Apple Cinnamon Cheerios   G enriched 146.6667  2.666667 2.666667
## 5:               Apple Jacks   K enriched 110.0000  2.000000 0.000000

Lets say I want to make a density plot for each of the numeric column values, colored by vitamin type. I could write eight different plots, or I could write a loop that creates plots, but it would be great if there were some way to plot all of them all at once.

facet_wrap seems like an obvious choice, but I cant use it with the dataset as it stands. facet_wrap only works when theres one column that has the names of the categories I want to facet on and one column that has the values of those categories. Why does that data structure sound familiar?

Lets see how we can easily make this plot:

# melt all numeric columns of the dataset
melted_UScereal <- melt(UScereal, id.vars=c("cereal_name", "mfr", "vitamins"))

print(head(melted_UScereal))
##                  cereal_name mfr vitamins variable    value
## 1:                 100% Bran   N enriched calories 212.1212
## 2:                  All-Bran   K enriched calories 212.1212
## 3: All-Bran with Extra Fiber   K enriched calories 100.0000
## 4:   Apple Cinnamon Cheerios   G enriched calories 146.6667
## 5:               Apple Jacks   K enriched calories 110.0000
## 6:                   Basic 4   G enriched calories 173.3333
# plot this melted dataset, faceting on the "variable" column
ggplot(melted_UScereal, aes(x=value)) +
  geom_density(aes(fill=vitamins), alpha=0.5)+
  facet_wrap(~variable, scales="free")


So much better than a loop, or eight completely individual plots! Reshaping is incredibly useful for plotting.

This is a lot of information, and ggplot takes some getting used to, but its just about the best plotting library Ive found in any programming language. I encourage you to practice on your own and see what you can come up with the ggplot cheat sheet, Wickhams ggplot chapter in R for Data Science, and the Internets forums are all there to help you when you get stuck.
